peopleAlsoAsk.question: What is my rocking horse worth?
peopleAlsoAsk.snippet: A 48" high Ayres or similar say £2,000 to £2,500. A 52" will be £3,000 to £3,500 and something about 55" high £5,000 to £6,000. Add £300 - £400 for "extra carving". A few really collectable horses, such as Ayres D types, swivel heads or spring stands will go even higher.

peopleAlsoAsk.question: How to identify Ayres rocking horse?
peopleAlsoAsk.snippet: Ayres rocking horses can, however, be recognised by their distinctive ring around the top of the vertical stand pillars, the finely carved heads with fragile lower jaws, slender legs and well-proportioned bodies with sloping rumps.

peopleAlsoAsk.question: What age is a rocking horse?
peopleAlsoAsk.snippet: A rocking horse might be a legend of the playroom, but when is it safe to introduce one to your child? This can depend on the kind of rocking horse you choose. A plush rocking horse with a backrest can be fun for your little one from the age of twelve months up, just in time for those toddler times!
